WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.429 --> 00:00:04.759
Jeff Huber: I'm Jeff Huber.
I'm SVP of engineering here at Google, responsible

00:00:04.759 --> 00:00:11.010
for ads and aps products.
And on behalf of Women at Google -- the group

00:00:11.010 --> 00:00:16.199
 -- and the "Talks at Google" series, please
join me in welcoming Padmasree Warrior, the

00:00:16.199 --> 00:00:17.571
CTO of Cisco.

00:00:17.571 --> 00:00:18.571
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

00:00:18.571 --> 00:00:26.850
Jeff Huber: She'll be speaking on "A Look
at The Future," which includes her perspective

00:00:26.850 --> 00:00:32.140
on market and technology transitions that
are changing the nature of work, how we connect,

00:00:32.140 --> 00:00:36.940
the future of computing -- including lots
of video and collaboration -- and I bet some

00:00:36.940 --> 00:00:41.630
thoughts on Smart Cities as well.
Prior to her role at Cisco, Padrasree was

00:00:41.630 --> 00:00:46.079
the CTO of Motorolla.
She joined Motorolla in 1984, rose through

00:00:46.079 --> 00:00:48.960
the ranks there to be responsible, to be their
CTO.

00:00:48.960 --> 00:00:55.329
And she directed Motorolla Labs, and led a
team of 26,000 engineers.

00:00:55.329 --> 00:01:01.003
She's very actively involved in the community
as well, is on the board of the Joffrey Ballet

00:01:01.003 --> 00:01:06.409
 -- and, being a Chicago native myself, one
of my favorite museums, the Museum of Science

00:01:06.409 --> 00:01:12.170
and Industry.
In 2004, she received the National Medal of

00:01:12.170 --> 00:01:17.770
Technology, and in 2007, was inducted into
the Women in Information Technology International's

00:01:17.770 --> 00:01:21.640
Hall of Fame.
And just last night was recognized by the

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:25.150
Forum for Women Entrepreneurs and Executives
with their Annual Achievement Award, which

00:01:25.150 --> 00:01:32.960
is a great accomplishment.
And given that this is a bit of a geeky audience,

00:01:32.960 --> 00:01:38.990
Padmasree also recently surpassed one million
Twitter followers, [laughter] and as you'll

00:01:38.990 --> 00:01:46.560
see, is far more interesting than Ashton Kutcher
or Oprah Winfrey.

00:01:46.560 --> 00:01:49.680
With that, Padmasree Warrior.

00:01:49.680 --> 00:01:50.680
&gt;&gt; [Clapping]

00:01:50.680 --> 00:01:56.070
Padmasree Warrior: Thanks, Jeff.
That's quite a generous introduction.

00:01:56.070 --> 00:01:59.159
Hi, everyone.
It's my great pleasure to be here today.

00:01:59.159 --> 00:02:03.790
I know some of the folks at Google have been
working very hard for over a year to get me

00:02:03.790 --> 00:02:11.989
here, so I appreciate very much your patience.
And it's actually a great opportunity to share

00:02:11.989 --> 00:02:17.040
my perspective on future and kind of treat
this more as a dialogue.

00:02:17.040 --> 00:02:22.939
Because I think, as we all know, any vision
we have for the future as time passes becomes

00:02:22.939 --> 00:02:27.840
very trite and mundane.
And that is really the power of technology.

00:02:27.840 --> 00:02:33.049
Innovation really is the magic that makes
imagination become a reality.

00:02:33.049 --> 00:02:38.810
So my goal is not so much just to see beyond
the future, but it's actually to enable it

00:02:38.810 --> 00:02:44.761
 -- enable it through technology.
And that's why I enjoy my role so much as

00:02:44.761 --> 00:02:48.139
the CTO.
So with that, what I want to do is to talk

00:02:48.139 --> 00:02:53.510
a little bit about how certain technologies
 -- certain technology frameworks -- are really

00:02:53.510 --> 00:03:01.510
going to change how and where work gets done
in the future, and also reflect a little bit

00:03:01.510 --> 00:03:07.379
on what "connected life" might look like,
and how Cisco and other companies in the technology

00:03:07.379 --> 00:03:11.719
industry are working hard to make all of this
a reality, and talk a little bit about the

00:03:11.719 --> 00:03:16.279
future of computing as a platform to do many
of these things.

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:22.199
And then, I want to share some views about
what all this means for business -- for leadership.

00:03:22.199 --> 00:03:27.309
And, in that context, I'll talk specifically
about women leaders, because that's a topic

00:03:27.309 --> 00:03:30.809
near and dear to my heart.
Lastly, about education.

00:03:30.809 --> 00:03:35.659
How might education look like in the future?
And hopefully, have lots of time for questions

00:03:35.659 --> 00:03:39.989
from the audience in the room and those that
are watching online.

00:03:39.989 --> 00:03:44.709
So, you know, if you think about future, one
of the things that we see happening is, more

00:03:44.709 --> 00:03:51.030
and more there is a demand for tools and applications
and platforms that enable intercompany collaboration.

00:03:51.030 --> 00:03:55.401
So a few years ago -- for those of us that
have been in the industry for a long time

00:03:55.401 --> 00:04:01.469
 -- a lot of companies and corporations focused
on enabling cross-functional teams and engineers

00:04:01.469 --> 00:04:05.749
to work more closely with designers and marketeers.
And really, it was all about How do you get

00:04:05.749 --> 00:04:10.760
diverse groups within a company to work together?
And the manufacturing industry probably pioneered

00:04:10.760 --> 00:04:15.879
a transition where they started to look beyond
their own walls, and started thinking about

00:04:15.879 --> 00:04:21.880
How do you extend business processes to include
suppliers, and not just suppliers from the

00:04:21.880 --> 00:04:26.860
point of purchase one step out, but multiple
steps out, and realize that there's a huge

00:04:26.860 --> 00:04:30.009
amount of productivity gains that they could
get from this.

00:04:30.009 --> 00:04:33.430
And many other verticals are now following
suit.

00:04:33.430 --> 00:04:38.010
So what does this mean?
This means now we have to think through developing

00:04:38.010 --> 00:04:42.590
enterprise applications that, not just connect
within the enterprise Internet work, but also

00:04:42.590 --> 00:04:46.139
go into the cloud and deploy certain applications
from the cloud.

00:04:46.139 --> 00:04:51.470
It brings very interesting challenges for
all of us in the industry to do that with

00:04:51.470 --> 00:04:54.970
security and interruptability.
Because each enterprise today uses different

00:04:54.970 --> 00:05:00.810
platforms to provide the connectivity.
At the same time, increasingly companies are

00:05:00.810 --> 00:05:06.199
depending on clusters of experts to get together
and work on critical projects.

00:05:06.199 --> 00:05:08.729
And, you know, this is a very interesting
idea also.

00:05:08.729 --> 00:05:14.850
At Cisco -- Cisco is a company with about
65,000 or so employees, over $30 billion in

00:05:14.850 --> 00:05:18.229
revenues.
We do business in almost every country on

00:05:18.229 --> 00:05:21.840
the planet.
And it's a company that's stitched together

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:26.520
with 130 acquisitions over its history of
25 years.

00:05:26.520 --> 00:05:32.800
And we just recently did an analysis.
We have close to 250 CEOs in the company.

00:05:32.800 --> 00:05:35.889
They all came from some form of an acquisition
or another.

00:05:35.889 --> 00:05:40.990
So the challenge is, How do you enable these
experts, these entrepreneurs, to create and

00:05:40.990 --> 00:05:46.840
innovate and tap into expertise that's outside
of the walls of the company, right?

00:05:46.840 --> 00:05:51.770
And so, the power of being able to do that
is, Experts choose the projects that they

00:05:51.770 --> 00:05:55.740
want to work on rather than being assigned
by their boss to go work on a project.

00:05:55.740 --> 00:06:02.591
And so, this is a dynamic process and it's
self-forming and improves agility and, in

00:06:02.591 --> 00:06:06.729
fact, produces better results.
So at Cisco, the way we drive innovation -- and

00:06:06.729 --> 00:06:13.760
we pursue at any time between 30 to 50 market
adjacencies, as we call it, are really a portfolio

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:18.249
of growth opportunities.
And part of my responsibility as the CTO is

00:06:18.249 --> 00:06:24.979
to make sure these portfolio growth opportunities
get the oxygen they need to foster the innovation

00:06:24.979 --> 00:06:31.830
within the company as well as tap into ideas
outside, right? So we have a program that

00:06:31.830 --> 00:06:36.020
we call I-Prize and I-Zone, where we collect
ideas from various parts of the globe and

00:06:36.020 --> 00:06:42.610
incorporate that into our own innovation portfolio.
So this notion is very interesting, because

00:06:42.610 --> 00:06:48.560
that sort of suggests that, perhaps organizations
will not be organized functionally or in a

00:06:48.560 --> 00:06:51.669
structured fashion in the future.
We have to think through How do we make these

00:06:51.669 --> 00:06:56.180
more social webs, almost, but in the context
of work.

00:06:56.180 --> 00:07:01.569
So, think of the postures of experts concept
to be at the foundation of that.

00:07:01.569 --> 00:07:08.180
The next major shift that will change how
work is perceived is, the emergence of millennials.

00:07:08.180 --> 00:07:12.979
So, people born after 1975.
Probably some of them may be in this room

00:07:12.979 --> 00:07:16.520
today.
And this generation brings with them the notion

00:07:16.520 --> 00:07:21.749
that they want to have access to work whenever
they want to work, right?

00:07:21.749 --> 00:07:27.680
So I always say this -- and already we do
this -- that the concept of "going to work"

00:07:27.680 --> 00:07:32.749
will go away in the future.
We will simply "do work" wherever we are.

00:07:32.749 --> 00:07:35.469
And that ties into the next trend, which is
mobility.

00:07:35.469 --> 00:07:41.340
Already there's a huge demand for -- and expectation
 -- that we will have access to every enterprise

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:46.289
application on any form of device, whether
we are mobile, fixed, or nomadic.

00:07:46.289 --> 00:07:51.150
And the access is really not pertinent.
And so, How do we solve that problem?

00:07:51.150 --> 00:07:56.949
So, what all of this means to the future of
work is, there's a huge demand for us to create

00:07:56.949 --> 00:08:05.650
a platform that now can integrate voice video
and data and provide those capabilities and

00:08:05.650 --> 00:08:11.710
applications in a secure, interoperable way,
both from on-premise access as well as in-the-cloud

00:08:11.710 --> 00:08:17.031
access, which is big set of challenges, but
lots of room for innovation for all of us

00:08:17.031 --> 00:08:21.009
to drive this.
The second area I want to talk about is "Connected

00:08:21.009 --> 00:08:23.639
Life.”
And again, you know, here mobility is a huge

00:08:23.639 --> 00:08:26.389
factor.
I used to work for a mobile company before

00:08:26.389 --> 00:08:33.120
I came to Cisco, and I often used to tell
people, "Every second on planet Earth there

00:08:33.120 --> 00:08:37.709
are four babies born.
Every second on planet Earth there are 32

00:08:37.709 --> 00:08:41.949
mobile phones sold.”
And so, the impact of what mobile communications

00:08:41.949 --> 00:08:47.950
is going to do to help people get connected
and communicate is just -- we probably haven't

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:53.120
even scratched the surface yet.
And I actually believe that the term "mobile

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:56.510
Internet" will be redundant in the future,
just like we don't say "mobile e-mail.”

00:08:56.510 --> 00:09:00.840
We just say "e-mail," and we expect to get
it wherever we are.

00:09:00.840 --> 00:09:06.209
Internet access will be very pervasive, and
hopefully seamless between whether we are

00:09:06.209 --> 00:09:11.579
mobile or whether we have a fixed access.
The second interesting thing in the "Connected

00:09:11.579 --> 00:09:14.640
Life" area -- and Cisco is driving a lot of
this -- is, video.

00:09:14.640 --> 00:09:20.920
Video, we believe, will be a killer ap in
the future -- everything from user-generated

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:24.269
video content.
We acquired recently a company called Pure

00:09:24.269 --> 00:09:28.490
Digital, which makes the Flip Video Cam -- high-density,
video camcorder, if you have one.

00:09:28.490 --> 00:09:34.199
And it's now become my favorite toy.
And we're trying to figure out, How do we

00:09:34.199 --> 00:09:38.889
bring that capability into the enterprise
phase, all the way to high-density, high-resolution,

00:09:38.889 --> 00:09:44.959
multipoint telepresence?
And then, with the availability of on-demand

00:09:44.959 --> 00:09:51.120
content now, consumers' expectation has shifted.
The debate is not really about content ownership

00:09:51.120 --> 00:09:54.639
anymore.
How do you consume content more in a community

00:09:54.639 --> 00:10:00.310
and make that a more community experience.
So we recently launched an initiative to wire

00:10:00.310 --> 00:10:05.741
up sports' stadiums -- Dallas Cowboy Stadium,
and a couple of other stadiums.

00:10:05.741 --> 00:10:08.970
And people often wonder, "What is Cisco doing
wiring stadiums up?”

00:10:08.970 --> 00:10:13.920
And the intent is not just to provide an immersive
video experience in the stadium, but we are

00:10:13.920 --> 00:10:16.630
working on, How do you extend that into the
home?

00:10:16.630 --> 00:10:21.389
So, from your home you can have an immersive
experience as if you're in the stadium watching

00:10:21.389 --> 00:10:27.220
your favorite sport.
So there is a lot we can do to sort of make

00:10:27.220 --> 00:10:33.610
content consumption much more interactive
and much more of a social experience in the

00:10:33.610 --> 00:10:36.149
future.
The other change that's driving "Connected

00:10:36.149 --> 00:10:39.910
Life," I would say, is more recent.
Probably this shift we've seen in the last

00:10:39.910 --> 00:10:43.350
six months or so.
And it's probably one of the good things that's

00:10:43.350 --> 00:10:47.949
come out of the economic crisis the world's
going through, and has gone through.

00:10:47.949 --> 00:10:52.269
And this is the fact that, there's now a lot
of stimulus money from many different governments

00:10:52.269 --> 00:10:58.860
around the world to think about how technology
can be applied to traditional protocols like

00:10:58.860 --> 00:11:04.829
healthcare, like transportation, like energy.
So a lot of recent movement in Smart Grid.

00:11:04.829 --> 00:11:09.560
For example, Smart Connected Cities, Smart
Buildings, How do you make buildings much

00:11:09.560 --> 00:11:15.390
more energy efficient, and What role does
IP Networking play to make that happen?”

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:19.970
Same thing in health care.
We are working on -- we have telepresence

00:11:19.970 --> 00:11:22.949
capability.
How do you extend that to promote and make

00:11:22.949 --> 00:11:28.089
remote health care available, where a doctor
can interface with a patient when proximity

00:11:28.089 --> 00:11:33.350
is not needed to provide health care to remote
locations where maybe there is no physical

00:11:33.350 --> 00:11:37.230
medical facility available, but we can provide
that through telepresence?

00:11:37.230 --> 00:11:41.810
So lots of things going on in, I would say,
what I would call "Lifestyle Optimization,"

00:11:41.810 --> 00:11:48.100
applying technology, and what we traditionally
thought of IT mostly as a B to B, but in different

00:11:48.100 --> 00:11:51.639
protocols, going into healthcare, sports,
education, etc.

00:11:51.639 --> 00:11:57.210
Lastly, Computing -- and probably this is
something you all know more than I do.

00:11:57.210 --> 00:12:02.610
Some of us have been in this industry long
enough to see the evolution from the 60's,

00:12:02.610 --> 00:12:07.660
from mainframes to minicomputers to PCs, more
recently, the web.

00:12:07.660 --> 00:12:10.569
And we believe the next evolution will be
to Cloud Computing.

00:12:10.569 --> 00:12:15.790
But we have to help enterprises make the transition,
because they already have a lot of investments

00:12:15.790 --> 00:12:20.190
that they've made in data centers.
And, How do you help take advantage of their

00:12:20.190 --> 00:12:26.750
investments companies have made with virtualization
so that you can scale Cloud Computing to become

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:33.680
more of a marketplace with workload portability,
federation, and security as to move data between

00:12:33.680 --> 00:12:36.980
the Cloud and apply with data center, for
instance.

00:12:36.980 --> 00:12:42.589
So that, we believe, is three big shifts that
we will see: Future of work, future of Connected

00:12:42.589 --> 00:12:46.190
Life, and Computing.
And then, you can kind of think and say, "Okay,

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:50.589
what does this mean to the Internet?" Wherever
we go -- wherever there is a platform for

00:12:50.589 --> 00:12:55.180
the next ten to 15 years.
And first, I want to look backwards and say,

00:12:55.180 --> 00:12:58.750
What did the Internet really allow us to do,
or What did we really focus on as an industry

00:12:58.750 --> 00:13:04.529
in the last maybe ten, 15, 20 years, right?
The network really focused on providing data

00:13:04.529 --> 00:13:07.310
transport.
It was really about moving small bits of data

00:13:07.310 --> 00:13:11.590
from point A to point B.
And e-mail was probably the killer ap in the

00:13:11.590 --> 00:13:15.050
first phase of the Internet.
And it was really a messaging platform.

00:13:15.050 --> 00:13:20.310
We all used it mostly for asynchronous messaging,
using e-mail initially.

00:13:20.310 --> 00:13:25.209
And the entire industry back then was focused
on optimizing price-performance ratios.

00:13:25.209 --> 00:13:29.430
So MIPS and megabits were the two metrics
we all focused on.

00:13:29.430 --> 00:13:33.519
Fastest network and most bandwidth that you
could push traffic through.

00:13:33.519 --> 00:13:39.200
And really didn't worry about things like
power consumption, cooling water requirements,

00:13:39.200 --> 00:13:42.279
data center footprint.
Those things were all afterthoughts.

00:13:42.279 --> 00:13:47.649
We didn't worry about those things.
And essentially, applications were vertically-integrated

00:13:47.649 --> 00:13:50.649
with infrastructure.
So if you had to deploy a new application

00:13:50.649 --> 00:13:54.069
and enterprise, you had to deploy new infrastructure
with it.

00:13:54.069 --> 00:13:58.259
So what we believe will happen in the second
phase of the Internet, or -- as I call it

00:13:58.259 --> 00:14:03.990
 -- the "Next Internet," is experiences now
have to scale almost exponentially as billions

00:14:03.990 --> 00:14:07.519
more devices and billions more people connect
to the network.

00:14:07.519 --> 00:14:11.800
Which means, now we have to think about the
network being more than data transport.

00:14:11.800 --> 00:14:15.680
It has to be enable media experience.
We've already seen this happen to the music

00:14:15.680 --> 00:14:20.120
industry.
Not too long ago, -used to buy pieces of furniture

00:14:20.120 --> 00:14:23.722
to store physical forms of music.
And you know?

00:14:23.722 --> 00:14:26.850
Now, I have this little thing that looks like
a dresser.

00:14:26.850 --> 00:14:31.259
It's camouflaged like a dresser, and if you
open it, there's drawers to store CDs in.

00:14:31.259 --> 00:14:33.259
It's become an antique now.
I don't know what to do with it.

00:14:33.259 --> 00:14:38.310
You know, so that how we consume music is
dramatically changed by the Internet.

00:14:38.310 --> 00:14:41.220
And the same thing I think will happen with
video next.

00:14:41.220 --> 00:14:46.480
And collaboration I already talked about.
The challenge we have is, How do you develop

00:14:46.480 --> 00:14:51.019
an enterprise-class collection platform and
bring things that are now in the consumer

00:14:51.019 --> 00:14:56.490
web with -- we just talked about Twitter,
and Jeff mentioned I have over a million followers

00:14:56.490 --> 00:14:57.490
on Twitter.
I love Twitter.

00:14:57.490 --> 00:15:01.060
I think it's just a great application.
Allows me to have conversations that I normally

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:08.250
wouldn't have in my normal course of the day,
and allows me to actually meet many new people

00:15:08.250 --> 00:15:11.420
on Twitter.
And so, How do you make those concepts come

00:15:11.420 --> 00:15:15.509
into the enterprise and make them more robust
to drive productivity in the enterprise?

00:15:15.509 --> 00:15:20.870
So that's really what I mean by "collaboration
enterprise platform" -- to engage in realtime

00:15:20.870 --> 00:15:26.329
interactive communications and create content
and create intellectual property together,

00:15:26.329 --> 00:15:32.199
both by participation from outside the corporation's
boundaries and inside -- the talent that's

00:15:32.199 --> 00:15:35.100
inside the corporation.
Last thing, sustainability.

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:40.380
And here kind of think about two areas.
One is, How do we apply Internet principles

00:15:40.380 --> 00:15:47.060
and IP networking to improve building's energy
efficiency, city's energy efficiency, etc.

00:15:47.060 --> 00:15:51.319
The other area is, How do you actually develop
IT itself to be more energy efficient?

00:15:51.319 --> 00:15:55.699
How do we build routing switching, data center
products to be much more energy efficient?

00:15:55.699 --> 00:16:00.709
So we focused on both those areas.
And lastly, Virtualization and Cloud Computing,

00:16:00.709 --> 00:16:06.750
How does that change compute, right?
But a prerequisite for all this is broadband

00:16:06.750 --> 00:16:10.829
penetration.
And I think that's where we're lagging behind

00:16:10.829 --> 00:16:13.769
in several parts of the world, including the
United States.

00:16:13.769 --> 00:16:18.829
And data says that actually ten percent increase
in broadband penetration in developing markets

00:16:18.829 --> 00:16:23.939
drives GDP up by 1.4 percent.
So, I think the challenge we all have in the

00:16:23.939 --> 00:16:27.490
industry is to drive that forward and make
sure there is broadband available, so that

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:32.820
we can deploy a lot of these technologies
and make the planet more smarter and greener.

00:16:32.820 --> 00:16:40.750
So at Cisco, we are focused in four areas
that drive our technology strategy very broadly.

00:16:40.750 --> 00:16:43.660
The first area is video.
Second is collaboration.

00:16:43.660 --> 00:16:47.300
Third is Smart, Connected Communities, and
I'll tell you a little bit about what we mean

00:16:47.300 --> 00:16:48.839
by that.
Virtualization and Cloud Computing.

00:16:48.839 --> 00:16:56.080
So, if you look at all of these, virtually,
a lot of these opportunities drive network

00:16:56.080 --> 00:16:59.649
traffic.
They drive bandwidth, and they drive innovation

00:16:59.649 --> 00:17:01.670
on the network.
And that's our agenda.

00:17:01.670 --> 00:17:09.630
And so, really you know, we expect that annual
IP traffic will reach two-thirds of a zettabite,

00:17:09.630 --> 00:17:17.950
or 667 exabites, by the end of this year.
So, if you think about it, by 2013 -- so about

00:17:17.950 --> 00:17:27.810
four years from now -- we will see global
IP traffic increase almost five-fold from

00:17:27.810 --> 00:17:32.460
where we are in 2009.
That's really mind-boggling if you think about

00:17:32.460 --> 00:17:36.650
it.
And on the consumer Internet today, about

00:17:36.650 --> 00:17:39.690
a third of the traffic is driven by Internet
video.

00:17:39.690 --> 00:17:49.280
So, thanks to YouTube and Hulu and others,
and Internet video itself in 2013 will be

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:55.390
almost 700 times bigger than the entire U.S.
Internet backbone was in the year 5000.

00:17:55.390 --> 00:18:00.571
So that was in 13 years.
And so, lots going on that will drive a lot

00:18:00.571 --> 00:18:07.030
of traffic onto the network.
The other interesting data point is actually

00:18:07.030 --> 00:18:12.510
mobile data.
By 2013, 62 percent of mobile data traffic

00:18:12.510 --> 00:18:16.060
will be video.
So a lot of applications that we can create

00:18:16.060 --> 00:18:19.120
and think about creating that will drive that
traffic.

00:18:19.120 --> 00:18:24.100
So we love video, all forms of video in any
form, and we're making big investments.

00:18:24.100 --> 00:18:28.360
You probably saw today Cisco announced our
intention to acquire Tandberg, which makes

00:18:28.360 --> 00:18:33.390
desktop video conferencing.
We already are a leader in very, high-end

00:18:33.390 --> 00:18:36.520
telepresence.
And I talked about Flip, so we are looking

00:18:36.520 --> 00:18:41.850
at video as an end-to-end architecture, everything
from user-generated video to high-density,

00:18:41.850 --> 00:18:47.140
high-resolution video.
Smart Connected Communities -- I want to talk

00:18:47.140 --> 00:18:51.830
about a little bit.
This is, you know really, I believe that we

00:18:51.830 --> 00:18:56.480
will evolve to what I call the "Industrialization
of the Internet.”

00:18:56.480 --> 00:19:01.850
And so here, the challenge really is, How
do you connect the cyber world with the physical

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:04.960
world?
So it's using sensor networks, perhaps.

00:19:04.960 --> 00:19:09.150
And not just actually connecting "people to
people," but "people to things" and "things

00:19:09.150 --> 00:19:11.820
to things.”
And this has been talked about for a number

00:19:11.820 --> 00:19:13.900
of years.
We've always talked about the Internet of

00:19:13.900 --> 00:19:16.510
Things.
But what is really driving an acceleration

00:19:16.510 --> 00:19:20.030
these days in this area is the rapid urbanization
of the planet.

00:19:20.030 --> 00:19:27.870
50 percent of the world's population by the
end of 2009 will live in cities.

00:19:27.870 --> 00:19:31.770
And these cities add roughly 180,000 people
every day.

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:36.440
That's like creating two new Tokyos every
year.

00:19:36.440 --> 00:19:42.940
And we expect that, by the year 2050, there
will be a hundred new cities with over a million

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:46.620
people each.
And, in one sense it's good, because a lot

00:19:46.620 --> 00:19:50.790
of the consumption happens in these cities,
but at the same time, you know, cities consume

00:19:50.790 --> 00:19:55.670
roughly 75 percent of the energy today, and
they produce 80 percent of the emissions.

00:19:55.670 --> 00:20:00.120
So the challenge we have is, How do we enable
these cities to be smarter?

00:20:00.120 --> 00:20:06.020
And we are launching pilots in South Korea
in cities like Icheon and Songdong where we

00:20:06.020 --> 00:20:10.270
are helping them build Smart Cities where
the network actually becomes a platform for

00:20:10.270 --> 00:20:15.190
enabling urban services, so where you can
get information about traffic on your mobile

00:20:15.190 --> 00:20:19.330
device.
We're enabling buses to have information about

00:20:19.330 --> 00:20:23.450
traffic congestion, and How do you route traffic,
and doing things like that.

00:20:23.450 --> 00:20:29.420
We're also working on making buildings smarter
by connecting HVAC systems with IP networks,

00:20:29.420 --> 00:20:31.920
so that you can bring those things onto a
same platform.

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:36.200
We acquired a company called Richards-Zeta
that has middleware capabilities that allows

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:43.600
us to do that, and we are bringing more intelligence
from the switching and routing into interconnecting

00:20:43.600 --> 00:20:48.880
the HVAC onto a single platform that can be
managed through software.

00:20:48.880 --> 00:20:55.050
Smart Grid is another area that's very interesting,
and we think that there will be 82 percent

00:20:55.050 --> 00:20:59.680
increase roughly in the energy demands globally
by the year 2020.

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:08.470
So, in the next 20 years or so roughly.
And DOE -- U.S. Department of Energy -- estimates

00:21:08.470 --> 00:21:14.420
that just modernization of the U.S. grids
alone will help us save roughly 50 to 100

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:17.530
billion dollars over the next 20 years or
so.

00:21:17.530 --> 00:21:23.990
So Smart Grids, if deployed properly, has
the capability to reduce peak loads by almost

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:27.990
15 percent annually.
And so, if you translate that, what that means

00:21:27.990 --> 00:21:32.351
is, in the U.S.
alone over the next 20 years, if we deployed

00:21:32.351 --> 00:21:39.830
Smart Grids, we would be able to save the
need -- or eliminate the need really -- for

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:45.050
almost a hundred large coal-fired, power plants.
So that's tremendous.

00:21:45.050 --> 00:21:48.770
That's almost like taking 30 million automobiles
off the road.

00:21:48.770 --> 00:21:53.320
So again, Smart Grid is another area where
we can think about, essentially our focus

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:59.750
is, How do you enable intelligent communication
between power-generation, transmission stations

00:21:59.750 --> 00:22:04.360
and home, connecting back into smart metering
at home or commercial buildings?

00:22:04.360 --> 00:22:10.930
And so, lots of exciting things.
And fundamentally, I believe that if you look

00:22:10.930 --> 00:22:17.180
forward ten years or so, six of the major
sectors will look very different from how

00:22:17.180 --> 00:22:22.580
we have been in the past.
You know, that's health care, transportation,

00:22:22.580 --> 00:22:30.090
energy, public services perhaps, you know,
IT or communications itself, and how technology

00:22:30.090 --> 00:22:34.300
gets deployed, etc.
So, you know, there's a lot of change going

00:22:34.300 --> 00:22:40.810
on, which then brings us to the question of,
How will business look like in the future?

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:44.350
And here, I'm speculating, so I'm really open
to a dialogue with you.

00:22:44.350 --> 00:22:50.120
I think really successful businesses in the
future have to be able to operate on multiple

00:22:50.120 --> 00:22:52.360
dimensions.
And I think many of us actually faced this

00:22:52.360 --> 00:22:56.220
challenge recently.
We have to innovate, and we have to focus

00:22:56.220 --> 00:22:59.930
on operational excellence.
In the past, it was okay to do one or the

00:22:59.930 --> 00:23:01.800
other.
I mean, there were companies that prided themselves

00:23:01.800 --> 00:23:06.260
on being very innovative, and there were companies
that prided themselves on being operationally

00:23:06.260 --> 00:23:09.170
really good.
And you know, they could get the maximum operating

00:23:09.170 --> 00:23:12.290
margins out just by squeezing costs and so
forth.

00:23:12.290 --> 00:23:15.060
And more and more, we are finding you have
to do both.

00:23:15.060 --> 00:23:18.790
And that, I think, brings up an interesting
challenge for all of us.

00:23:18.790 --> 00:23:23.320
And the other interesting thing is, we have
to have global scale, because it is a connected

00:23:23.320 --> 00:23:27.280
world and economies are connected -- as we
found out recently as well.

00:23:27.280 --> 00:23:31.950
But you have to have agility at the same time
along with the global scale, and How do we

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:35.240
do that?
And the other thing that's interesting.

00:23:35.240 --> 00:23:39.660
I just read recently a report that said, high
school students or actually, even middle school

00:23:39.660 --> 00:23:43.760
students or kids between the ages of 13 to,
I think, 19.

00:23:43.760 --> 00:23:48.480
And there was a survey that was done, and
almost 75 percent of them said that they do

00:23:48.480 --> 00:23:52.670
not want to work for a big company.
So you can kind of think of this environment

00:23:52.670 --> 00:23:55.690
in the future where there will probably be
all these little start-ups.

00:23:55.690 --> 00:23:58.880
Or small companies, right?
And so, What is the notion of a big company

00:23:58.880 --> 00:24:01.860
anymore, and How will that change?
What does that mean to business?

00:24:01.860 --> 00:24:05.240
Which brings me to, How will leadership change
in the future?

00:24:05.240 --> 00:24:09.711
And I spoke last night about -- in the context
of women's leadership -- and maybe this is

00:24:09.711 --> 00:24:14.240
more of my perspective as a woman leader,
but I think it applies broadly to leaders

00:24:14.240 --> 00:24:17.480
as well.
You know, traditionally leadership was about

00:24:17.480 --> 00:24:20.870
commanding and making decisions.
I had a team of 26,000 engineers in my previous

00:24:20.870 --> 00:24:26.090
job, and it was great power.
If I said, "Do this," and I could feel like

00:24:26.090 --> 00:24:30.230
everybody would do it.
But I think, more and more, leadership is

00:24:30.230 --> 00:24:33.940
about influence.
It's, How do you get companies to change direction

00:24:33.940 --> 00:24:38.080
or Industry to change direction or Government
to change direction?

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:42.570
And that means leaders have to now figure
out, How do you expand your sphere of influence?

00:24:42.570 --> 00:24:46.850
It's not just what you control, but it's,
How do you influence outside your boundaries?

00:24:46.850 --> 00:24:49.600
And this is where a lot of the social networking
tools help us.

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:55.470
I think Twitter -- I spoke last night about
how it helps me expand my sphere of influence.

00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:59.240
This is a skill leaders didn't have to worry
about a few years ago.

00:24:59.240 --> 00:25:02.120
In fact, leaders prided themselves about being
very private.

00:25:02.120 --> 00:25:06.640
We were told, "You can't say some things in
public." "Don't say that.”

00:25:06.640 --> 00:25:10.120
PR always told us, "Don't do that," "Don't
say this.”

00:25:10.120 --> 00:25:13.420
And so, now we have to figure out, "Well,
say it." but "How do you say it?" What do

00:25:13.420 --> 00:25:15.600
you say?
And, What not to say?

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:19.510
And, How do you -- the fact that you belong
to multiple communities is a strength, and

00:25:19.510 --> 00:25:24.000
that's another area where you can expand your
sphere of influence, right?

00:25:24.000 --> 00:25:28.800
For example, I belong to a community of engineers.
I belong to a community of Silicon Valley

00:25:28.800 --> 00:25:30.830
leaders.
I belong to a community of women.

00:25:30.830 --> 00:25:35.490
I belong to a community of working mothers.
I went to Cornell, so I belong to a Cornell

00:25:35.490 --> 00:25:38.320
Alumni community.
There's various communities we belong to,

00:25:38.320 --> 00:25:43.050
and more and more, a challenge for all of
us, as we become leaders is, How do you leverage

00:25:43.050 --> 00:25:47.780
these communities, and, In what way is it
appropriate to bring some of these communities

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:51.870
to overlap in what you are doing?
So those are some new leadership skills that

00:25:51.870 --> 00:25:57.830
we would have to learn.
The second skill is about collaboration.

00:25:57.830 --> 00:26:01.161
And this is interesting, because I actually
think of collaboration as being very different

00:26:01.161 --> 00:26:05.780
from teamwork or "consensus-driven committees"
as we used to call them, right?

00:26:05.780 --> 00:26:09.750
You know, it's not -- collaboration doesn't
necessarily mean teamwork and everybody gets

00:26:09.750 --> 00:26:13.370
along and does things.
It actually means you're okay in sharing an

00:26:13.370 --> 00:26:18.320
idea before it's fully formulated.
You have an idea, and you want to share that

00:26:18.320 --> 00:26:23.350
so other people can add -- other experts can
add -- to that idea to make it stronger.

00:26:23.350 --> 00:26:26.060
And, How do we do that?
What's the right way to do it?

00:26:26.060 --> 00:26:29.890
And, What's the most appropriate to do it
quickly, so that you are not forever gathering

00:26:29.890 --> 00:26:33.260
input.
At some point you have to move on.

00:26:33.260 --> 00:26:36.320
So collaboration -- how to collaborate.
What it means, I think, is another leadership

00:26:36.320 --> 00:26:44.530
skill that we would have to garner.
And the third is really, being more than just

00:26:44.530 --> 00:26:48.340
being a pioneer or a trailblazer.
And again, this is in the context of women

00:26:48.340 --> 00:26:52.780
that I talked about last night at this forum
for women entrepreneurs and executives.

00:26:52.780 --> 00:26:58.410
When I started in the industry almost 20 years
ago, there were very few women -- in engineering,

00:26:58.410 --> 00:27:02.680
especially, and in leadership positions.
So there were women that were considered to

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:09.100
be trailblazers and pioneers, who sort of
formed the way, and we were told we had to

00:27:09.100 --> 00:27:12.761
be different.
Women were told they had to dress different,

00:27:12.761 --> 00:27:16.420
act different, speak different, maybe more
like a man, dress like a man.

00:27:16.420 --> 00:27:20.780
I think more and more, what people really
appreciate is authenticity.

00:27:20.780 --> 00:27:23.160
Leadership is all about being real, who you
are.

00:27:23.160 --> 00:27:28.091
So I encourage all the women to really be
women, and be successful by the fact that

00:27:28.091 --> 00:27:32.620
you are a woman leader and a woman engineer,
or a technical or marketing expert, or whatever

00:27:32.620 --> 00:27:35.291
it is.
So I think this notion of trying to be different

00:27:35.291 --> 00:27:40.420
or being a pioneer by being different is going
to change in the future.

00:27:40.420 --> 00:27:44.410
So I think those are some things that I think
about how leaders of the future, some of the

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:49.320
challenges that they will have to deal with.
Which brings me next to education.

00:27:49.320 --> 00:27:54.470
And this might be controversial, but I actually
think there's a big difference between education

00:27:54.470 --> 00:27:57.790
and learning.
And if you think about it, right?

00:27:57.790 --> 00:28:03.440
The famous Einstein quote about -- I forget
the exact quote, but it's something like,

00:28:03.440 --> 00:28:06.560
"It's a miracle that curiosity survives formal
education.”

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:11.470
And in a way, it's so true, because now content
is available.

00:28:11.470 --> 00:28:17.010
And so, the fact that education is really
about teaching content has to change.

00:28:17.010 --> 00:28:21.850
It has to become more about How do you teach
how to learn, because students these days

00:28:21.850 --> 00:28:25.000
can access content anywhere.
So, What do you do with that content?

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:30.810
How do you actually make -- my view is education
is more discreet, it has a beginning and an

00:28:30.810 --> 00:28:36.450
end in some ways, whereas learning is continuous.
We have to teach our children how to learn

00:28:36.450 --> 00:28:38.651
continuously.
And, What do you do with all this information

00:28:38.651 --> 00:28:41.670
that's available? And, How do you create something
with it?

00:28:41.670 --> 00:28:46.660
So I think education perhaps will also take
on a new meaning in the future and become

00:28:46.660 --> 00:28:52.250
more about learning -- I hope, anyway.
So I'll stop there and take questions from

00:28:52.250 --> 00:28:58.110
all of you if you have any.
I think that's my last step.

00:28:58.110 --> 00:29:02.040
And I think there's a microphone on the side.

