00:29:04.660 --> 00:29:14.580
Q I go to the microphone so people can hear
me.

00:29:14.580 --> 00:29:21.870
You mentioned really needing to drive innovation
and operational excellence, which has been

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:28.400
not historically viewed as necessarily complementary.
Agree that that is the necessity and reality

00:29:28.400 --> 00:29:33.740
of today.
How do you think about that with your teams?

00:29:33.740 --> 00:29:35.840
And as a leader at Cisco applying that across
Cisco?

00:29:35.840 --> 00:29:39.770
Padmasree Warrior: That's a great question.
It's a very tough thing, because right now,

00:29:39.770 --> 00:29:42.960
I think innovators pride themselves as not
being process-driven.

00:29:42.960 --> 00:29:45.860
They don't want to follow process.
Process is evil.

00:29:45.860 --> 00:29:49.160
And people that are good at process think
of innovators as being these crazy people

00:29:49.160 --> 00:29:51.760
that just keep coming up with ideas and they
don't know what to do with them.

00:29:51.760 --> 00:29:56.880
You know, and I said as a company we were
pursuing 30 adjacencies, which is a lot for

00:29:56.880 --> 00:30:00.280
a big company.
And each of those we expect to be a billion-dollar

00:30:00.280 --> 00:30:02.900
opportunity almost.
So that's where we expect our next $30 billion

00:30:02.900 --> 00:30:07.020
of growth to come from.
And we think we have to go to 50.

00:30:07.020 --> 00:30:09.070
And so, one of the challenges is, "Okay, What
do you do?

00:30:09.070 --> 00:30:12.650
How do you know which ones of these are right?”
And "How do you know which ones you want to

00:30:12.650 --> 00:30:15.230
accelerate and doubledown on, and which ones
you want to slow down?”

00:30:15.230 --> 00:30:19.840
So I actually came up with this methodology
with some of my peers at Cisco.

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:23.601
We've taken Geoffrey Moore's Chasm Model -- if
you are familiar with that -- which talks

00:30:23.601 --> 00:30:28.800
about technology at option life cycle, and
there's a chasm and there's prechasm, post-chasm.

00:30:28.800 --> 00:30:32.720
And we've actually taken that, and most of
the growth opportunities, if you think about

00:30:32.720 --> 00:30:36.540
it, fall in the prechasm mode.
You know, when you're an innovator, you're

00:30:36.540 --> 00:30:40.130
thinking about something that's still early.
You probably don't know if there's going to

00:30:40.130 --> 00:30:43.650
be a market yet.
And so, how you measure that is going to be

00:30:43.650 --> 00:30:46.830
very different than something that's going
to be more of a mature business.

00:30:46.830 --> 00:30:53.740
And we have come up with ways, by allowing
different types to measure progress on something

00:30:53.740 --> 00:30:57.610
that's innovative, but there is still measurement.
And you still have to.

00:30:57.610 --> 00:31:01.652
You know, I tell people this, "You don't graduate
with your Ph.D. just because you're brilliant.

00:31:01.652 --> 00:31:04.350
You still have to defend your thesis.
There's a process.

00:31:04.350 --> 00:31:08.620
And there's a gate you have to go through.”
Similarly, if you're asking for funding within

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:12.570
a company or from an outside company, you
still have to hit some metrics.

00:31:12.570 --> 00:31:15.750
And so, we're trying to put some of those
metrics in the discipline, but at the same

00:31:15.750 --> 00:31:18.290
time allowing people the freedom to create
and come up with great ideas.

