00:37:02.069 --> 00:37:07.440
Q Hi. I'm a product manager in one of the
research teams here, and one of the things

00:37:07.440 --> 00:37:13.359
I think about a lot is "productizing research.”
I'm curious to hear your views on, What are

00:37:13.359 --> 00:37:17.680
some effective ways to accelerate that research
to product? Specifically, because Cisco in

00:37:17.680 --> 00:37:25.420
general I see as a company that does R&amp;D by
acquisition for the most part.

00:37:25.420 --> 00:37:29.680
And from your experience in Motorolla, I'm
curious to hear what do you think works and

00:37:29.680 --> 00:37:30.680
what doesn't?

00:37:30.680 --> 00:37:34.859
Padmasree Warrior: Yeah. That's a great question.
You know, I think they're very different models.

00:37:34.859 --> 00:37:40.780
When I was at Motorolla, we had a research
lab with close to 800 people that were doing

00:37:40.780 --> 00:37:44.070
essentially, I would say, pretty fundamental
research, working with universities.

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:48.900
And then, we had a very disciplined way of
transferring that into commercialization.

00:37:48.900 --> 00:37:51.260
Cisco here, right?
We have a very small focus on research.

00:37:51.260 --> 00:37:56.490
Mostly, we fund universities to do the research.
The philosophy at Cisco is that, We let the

00:37:56.490 --> 00:38:00.310
people that are really good at doing research
do the research, and we will either acquire

00:38:00.310 --> 00:38:06.209
or create, focus more on developing.
But we do tap into -- Cisco uses what I call

00:38:06.209 --> 00:38:11.720
 -- I was talking about this earlier, this
notion of I-Prize and I-Zone -- very effectively,

00:38:11.720 --> 00:38:17.049
where we post a problem and let innovators
bid on it, and we have a competition and whoever

00:38:17.049 --> 00:38:22.440
wins, and the competition, I mean, it's judged
by independent judges, not just Cisco teams.

00:38:22.440 --> 00:38:25.210
We have VCs and people from academia participate
in that.

00:38:25.210 --> 00:38:30.319
And the winning idea gets $250,000 seed-funding
from Cisco.

00:38:30.319 --> 00:38:33.910
And we usually negotiate something for the
intellectual property, and so forth.

00:38:33.910 --> 00:38:38.009
So we do it that way at Cisco.
But I think -- to answer your question about

00:38:38.009 --> 00:38:42.450
some of the things from overall my experience
about research -- it's very important to do

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:46.940
research, because that's how you discover
things, you know, which is mostly in the invention

00:38:46.940 --> 00:38:49.840
phase.
The challenge is, How do you translate those

00:38:49.840 --> 00:38:54.410
inventions to innovations, right?
And this is where you have to tie very closely

00:38:54.410 --> 00:38:56.490
with, What is the market transition going
to be?

00:38:56.490 --> 00:39:00.869
I think it's very critical.
One of the big challenges in bringing things

00:39:00.869 --> 00:39:05.130
to market is actually catching the transition
at the right time.

00:39:05.130 --> 00:39:09.130
You know, timing is very important, because
you can be too early in the market and have

00:39:09.130 --> 00:39:13.420
a failed product, or you can be too late,
at which point, you won't make very good margins.

00:39:13.420 --> 00:39:17.349
And so, you have to get the timing right.
And the biggest challenge that I felt when

00:39:17.349 --> 00:39:21.700
I was leading research organizations is getting
the timing right on when you take something

00:39:21.700 --> 00:39:27.400
out of research and move it more into product
development, and How does that hand-off happen?

00:39:27.400 --> 00:39:32.020
And so, to do that, really, you need to have
input from multiple directions, right?

00:39:32.020 --> 00:39:36.430
You have to have a feel for, What are the
global trends in the market dynamics? And

00:39:36.430 --> 00:39:40.110
sometimes it's hard to predict.
That's, like I was talking about, the "Internet

00:39:40.110 --> 00:39:43.490
of Things" has been in research phase almost
for 10, 15 years.

00:39:43.490 --> 00:39:47.559
People have been working on sensor networks.
But it's only recently, we've seen commercial

00:39:47.559 --> 00:39:52.299
need for it, mainly driven by Smart Grid.
And the Smart Grid demand happened because

00:39:52.299 --> 00:39:55.200
energy has become a problem.
Now, there's stimulus money going into it.

00:39:55.200 --> 00:39:58.940
So other factors change that.
So somehow, you have to have a feel and your

00:39:58.940 --> 00:40:03.589
finger on the pulse of the changes that are
going on in the marketplace.

00:40:03.589 --> 00:40:07.940
And whether you do that in the research organization,
or you work with other parts of Google that

00:40:07.940 --> 00:40:13.690
does that, I think that's very critical.

