00:48:18.460 --> 00:48:20.920
sake.
I think you have to think about, How do you

00:48:20.920 --> 00:48:25.509
use the process to help people accelerate
what they're working on?

00:48:25.509 --> 00:48:32.119
Right? So the way we've been able to develop
that is to sort of look at, you know, the

00:48:32.119 --> 00:48:37.730
30 or 50 ajacencies that we are pursuing.
And they vary -- everything from putting a

00:48:37.730 --> 00:48:42.319
router in space to using video as the next
big architecture, right?

00:48:42.319 --> 00:48:47.630
One is very big, one is a very niche opportunity.
Highly technically challenging to think about

00:48:47.630 --> 00:48:51.950
routers in space, and they require very different
kinds of metrics.

00:48:51.950 --> 00:48:57.989
And so, the process has to be such that, it's
really flexible to allow that diversity that

00:48:57.989 --> 00:49:00.559
innovators need and the room they need to
create.

00:49:00.559 --> 00:49:04.230
And it's not about -- you shouldn't measure
them on Did you make a mistake, and How many

00:49:04.230 --> 00:49:07.160
mistakes you made.
It's not defects that count, right?

00:49:07.160 --> 00:49:11.029
It's not the traditional quality metric.
But it's, What do you do when you make a mistake,

00:49:11.029 --> 00:49:15.070
and How do you -- when you find that you have
an experiment and it didn't yield the results

00:49:15.070 --> 00:49:19.660
you were expecting, that's still a result.
And so, you have to accept that as a success

00:49:19.660 --> 00:49:25.910
and go to the next thing.
So it's actually having that type of flexibility

00:49:25.910 --> 00:49:29.859
in the process, I think, is very important.
Otherwise, you get very bureaucratic and bogged

00:49:29.859 --> 00:49:36.099
down and nothing ever gets done.

00:49:36.099 --> 00:49:41.150
Q So I have a question.
