Cisco can do to retain and attract, you know,

00:49:51.000 --> 00:49:52.404
talented youth to come and work for their
companies?

00:49:52.404 --> 00:49:56.540
I imagine these are the type of people who
have the entrepreneurship and innovation to

00:49:56.540 --> 00:50:00.579
really help make any company great.
And so, it seems like it would be important

00:50:00.579 --> 00:50:02.079
to attract or retain them.

00:50:02.079 --> 00:50:07.670
Padmasree Warrior: Yeah. This was actually
a report I had read that talked about how

00:50:07.670 --> 00:50:12.640
schools students -- when asked what they want
to do -- almost 80 percent of them or something

00:50:12.640 --> 00:50:16.569
said they don't want to work for a big company.
They want to work for little companies with

00:50:16.569 --> 00:50:20.210
few people, which made me think, "Well, what
does that mean to companies, right?

00:50:20.210 --> 00:50:24.750
In the future, How will they operate?”
So that's kind of where I was quoting that

00:50:24.750 --> 00:50:26.650
data from.
What I think we can do, and what we should

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:30.150
do is, sort of create that agility within
a big company.

00:50:30.150 --> 00:50:33.390
Big companies, by the way, have a lot of advantages,
right?

00:50:33.390 --> 00:50:38.660
And there was an article in The Economist
recently that talked about how, "Big is Back.”

00:50:38.660 --> 00:50:44.019
I think when times get tough, having scale
helps.

00:50:44.019 --> 00:50:49.380
Then being part of a big company is very attractive,
because you know you have cash, you have very

00:50:49.380 --> 00:50:53.299
high margins, and the business is not going
to go away, and you can take the hit for a

00:50:53.299 --> 00:50:57.900
few months or a few years and come back.
So there's definite advantages to scale, but

00:50:57.900 --> 00:51:01.329
we have to combine the agility and the flexibility
with the scale.

00:51:01.329 --> 00:51:04.749
And I think this is a generational shift that
we will see.

00:51:04.749 --> 00:51:10.329
As kids that are growing up -- I have a teenage
son, and to him e-mail is dead.

00:51:10.329 --> 00:51:14.340
I mean dead.
If I e-mail him, I have to text him or post

00:51:14.340 --> 00:51:18.079
an update on his Facebook saying, "I've sent
you an e-mail, please go read it.”

00:51:18.079 --> 00:51:21.570
And he always asks me, "Mom, why do you leave
me a voice mail on my mobile phone?

00:51:21.570 --> 00:51:24.020
I know I have a missed call, and I know you
called me.

00:51:24.020 --> 00:51:26.499
I'll call you back.”
He never checks his voice mail, which is very

00:51:26.499 --> 00:51:29.819
frustrating to me, because I grew up with
e-mail and voice mail.

00:51:29.819 --> 00:51:32.960
So I think this notion.
I mean, what they require is very different,

00:51:32.960 --> 00:51:36.690
so we have to figure out what motivates them.
It's the flexibility, it's the ability to

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:41.349
"do work" not necessarily to "go to work.”
And, How do you enable that to happen?

00:51:41.349 --> 00:51:45.079
I think those kinds of things -- we have to
give them that flexibility yet be attached

00:51:45.079 --> 00:51:49.349
to a more stable entity, perhaps, which could
be attractive.

